  Step-by-Step Breakdown
  
  Step 1 — Flow triggers the Apex Action

  When your Flow hits the "Create QuickBooks Customer" action element,
  Salesforce calls:

  @InvocableMethod(label='Create QuickBooks Customer')
  public static void createCustomer(List<CustomerInput> inputs)

  The @InvocableMethod annotation is what makes this method visible to Flow. The
  Flow passes field values (name, email, phone, etc.) into the CustomerInput
  object — each field mapped in Flow corresponds to an @InvocableVariable in the
  CustomerInput inner class.

  ---
  Step 2 — Builds the QuickBooks customer object

  CustomerInput input = inputs.get(0);  // always takes the first record

  QBCustomerInput customer = new QBCustomerInput();
  customer.DisplayName = input.quickbooksName;
  // ... maps all fields

  It takes the Flow input and maps it into a QBCustomerInput object — which is a
  separate class that matches QuickBooks' API expected format. Email and Phone
  are nested objects because QuickBooks API expects them that way:

  QBCustomerInput.PrimaryEmailAddr email = new
  QBCustomerInput.PrimaryEmailAddr();
  email.Address = input.primaryEmail;
  customer.PrimaryEmailAddr = email;

  ---
  Step 3 — Why it serializes to JSON and calls @future
  
  String customerJson = System.JSON.serialize(customer);
  QBCreateCustomerAction.createCustomerAsync(customerJson);

  This is solving a critical Salesforce limitation:

  ▎ You cannot make an HTTP callout in the same transaction as a DML operation.

  Flows often do DML (insert/update records) before calling an Apex action. If
  you tried to make the QuickBooks API call directly in createCustomer(),
  Salesforce would throw a System.CalloutException: You have uncommitted work 
  pending.

  The fix:
  - Serialize the object to a JSON string (since @future methods can only accept
  primitive types — no objects)
  - Hand it off to createCustomerAsync() which runs in a separate transaction
  where callouts are allowed

  ---
  Step 4 — @future method makes the actual API call

  @future(callout=true)
  public static void createCustomerAsync(String customerJson) {
      QBCustomerInput customer = (QBCustomerInput)
  System.JSON.deserialize(customerJson, QBCustomerInput.class);
      QBSyncCustomer.createCustomer(customer);
  }

  - Deserializes the JSON string back into a QBCustomerInput object
  - Calls QBSyncCustomer.createCustomer(customer) — this is where the actual
  HTTP POST to QuickBooks API happens (defined in the QBSyncCustomer class)
  - callout=true on @future explicitly enables HTTP callouts in that async
  context

  ---
  Flow of Data — Visual Summary
  
  Flow (passes field values)
          ↓
  createCustomer() — builds QBCustomerInput, serializes to JSON
          ↓
  createCustomerAsync() — @future, new transaction
          ↓
  QBSyncCustomer.createCustomer() — HTTP callout to QuickBooks API

